FBIS3-55309 "drsov005_s_94002" FBIS-SOV-94-005 Document Type:Daily Report 7 Jan 1994 Georgia Reportage on Gamsakhurdia's Reported Death Aides Deny Rumors; Shevardnadze Comments LD0601185794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 1700 GMT 6 Jan 94 LD0601185794 Moscow Russian Television Network Language: Russian Article Type:BFN [From the "Vesti" newscast] [Excerpts] [Studio announcer] Mystery continues to surround the story of the suicide of Zviad Gamsakhurdia. The Georgian leadership is not cofirming or denying these reports. [passage omitted] [Correspondent N.Kandiashvili] Where does the reality about Gamsakhurdia lie, among the hundreds of different versions of his death? [passage omitted -- a Chechen delegation told Shevardnadze of the death] Regarding the rumors that he was surrounded by armed Georgian units and forced to shoot himself, in a special interview for "Vesti," Eduard Shevardnadze said today: [Begin Shevardnadze recording] I categorically deny this because we did not plan any military operations, and there was no such pursuit. And there was no need for such a thing since we considered and we still consider that he is not a serious political force. And if indeed he has been killed or has committed suicide, I am sincerely hurt. [end recording] [Studio announcer] Gamsakhurdia's representative in Spain, (Zhordani), has stated that the former president of Georgia is still alive. Zhordani claims that the suicide reports are aimed at bringing Gamsakhurdia out of his refuge in Georgia in order to arrest him. Valeriya Novodvorskaya, adviser to Zviad Gamsakhurdia, expressed her opinion today. [Begin Novodvorskaya recording] I can state quite positively that nothing has happened yet. The president of Georgia is still alive. We are in constant contact with the president. Everyone who knows Zviad can only deride the story about the suicide of a deeply religious Christian and a man who bears responsibility for his cause and for his country. [end recording]
